   <mods:abstract>ALS. Written by Jay as Secretary for Foreign Affairs under the
            Confederation government to Price, a dissenting minister and pamphleteer in Britain who
            supported American independence. Apologizes to Price for being tardy in responding and
            thanks him for sending copies of his pamphlet (a reference to Price's pamphlet
            "Observations on the importance of the American Revolution, and the means of making it a
            benefit to the world." which Price had sent Jay in 1784, and which among other themes
            argued for elimination of slavery in America). Jay says "I am not without Hopes that
            Time and Experience will yet bring our political system to that Degree of Perfection,
            which may reasonably be expected in human Institutions," adding "popular Governments
            must be influenced by popular opinion, and popular opinion must be created not
            commanded," a process that can "proceed but slowly." Jay notes that Price's pamphet has
            been reprinted, read, and admired in America and that Price's character, integrity, and
            abilities are well respected there.</mods:abstract>
